From: DBruno@gnn.com (DWIGHT BRUNO)
I hope it goes without saying that the cats that are captured (after
having bitten, scratched or otherwise exposed a person or pet) are
not disposed of before rabies status is determined unless a bite or
scatch from a feral cat is considererd enough of a reason to go
ahead with post exposure rabies prophylaxis in a person or booster
an actively immunized pet for which there is an approved rabies
vaccine. The reason for my concern is related to what we are going
through all over NYS as far as rabies (raccoon strain)...as you are
probably aware, cats are a major problem and concern with regard to
human exposures.
Dwight Bruno
