[2]
From: Drzero@aol.com
Date: Sat, 9 Mar 1996 13:34:39 -0500
I have no statistics nor study data, but we spay/neuter many cats each year.
This in no way stops their predation on wildlife as the owners report to
us.
My father, also a Veterinarian, spayed and declawed all 4 feet of a small
black and white cat we kept at the hospital in suburban Chicago. Our house
was 100 feet behind the hospital. This was also our pet cat. This cat would
climb 6 feet up a limbless Elm tree, bring back birds, mice and even young
rabbits. Being declawed and neutered in no way slowed nor prevented her
hunting/predation traits!
Peter Cyrog, DVM
Azusa, California
Dr zero @ Aol.com
